  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several important ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Provide standardized frameworks for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate on investigations\n- Share financial intelligence\n- Extradite suspects\n- Freeze and confiscate criminal assets\n\n3. Regulatory Compliance\n- Countries adopt similar legal standards\n- Require financial institutions to implement anti-money laundering (AML) controls\n- Establish Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Monitor suspicious transactions\n\n4. Jurisdictional Cooperation\n- Cross-border information sharing\n- Coordinated enforcement actions\n- Unified definitions of money laundering offenses\n\n5. Sanctions and Penalties\n- Consistent international standards\n- Harmonized approach to prosecuting financial crimes\n- Deterrence through coordinated enforcement\n\n6. Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs)\n- International networks of financial crime investigators\n- Exchange information across borders\n- Develop sophisticated tracking mechanisms\n\nThese intersections create a complex but increasingly sophisticated global approach to preventing money laundering.",
